paragraphs.title: Read in CSV file for linear regression
paragraphs.text:
val linearDF = sqlContext.read
    .format("com.databricks.spark.csv")
    .option("header", "true") // Use first line of all files as header
    .option("inferSchema", "false") // Automatically infer data types)
    .option("nullValue", "empty")
    .option("dateFormat", "yyyy-MM-dd")
    .schema(customSchema)
    .load("/resources/data/nba-datawrangle-lrDF.csv")
    .withColumn("label", $"fscorea")

paragraphs.title: Build Linear Regression ML Pipeline - Predict  Home / Away team scores
paragraphs.text:
// Linear regression requires that
// The best way I found to modify data in a custom way is with map, however it returns an RDD, so you will need to run toDF at the end
// Logistic DF requires a DF of type  => [label: double, features: vector]



// Configure an ML pipeline, which consists of two stages: assembler and linear regression

val assembler_ab = new VectorAssembler()
  .setInputCols(Array("scorea", "scoreb", "teama_adj_fscore", "teamb_adj_fscore", "timeleft", "overunder", "teama_vegas_fscore", "teamb_vegas_fscore","teamaspread" ))
  .setOutputCol("features")

//val output = assembler_a.transform(linearDF)
  
val lr_a = new LinearRegression()
  .setMaxIter(50)
  .setRegParam(0.01)
  .setLabelCol("fscorea")
  .setFeaturesCol("features")

val pipeline_a = new Pipeline()
  .setStages(Array(assembler_ab, lr_a))

// Fit the pipeline to training documents.
val model_a = pipeline_a.fit(trainingdf)
val predictions_a = model_a.transform(testdf)

val lr_b = new LinearRegression()
  .setMaxIter(50)
  .setRegParam(0.01)
  .setLabelCol("fscoreb")
  .setFeaturesCol("features")

val pipeline_b = new Pipeline()
  .setStages(Array(assembler_ab, lr_b))

// Fit the pipeline to training documents.
val model_b = pipeline_b.fit(trainingdf)
val predictions_b = model_b.transform(testdf)

paragraphs.title: Linear Model Analysis And Explanation
paragraphs.text:
%md 
    
  Linear Model Discussion
    Model A Intercept = 18.67585111005019
                           "scorea", "scoreb", "teama_adj_fscore", "teamb_adj_fscore", "timeleft", "overunder", "teama_vegas_fscore", "teamb_vegas_fscore","teamaspread" 
    Model A weight Vector = [-0.0993 , 0.177   ,  1.00             ,  -0.059           , 0.131     , -0.049     , -0.010              , -0.0895             ,-0.056]

  the features with a positive sign contribute to the predicted score when the corresponding feature increase while it is the opposite for the features with a negative sign.
  Lets look at time left as an example.  If time left in the game increases by one minute, the additive effect is that the final score will increase by 0.131 pts.
  However this is made more complicated by the fact that I added a custom feature called  teama_adj_fscore (teama projected final score based on time left and predicted vegas score).
  
  This makes it more difficult to directly assess the contribution to a single feature by directly looking at the weights since other features are also correlated to them.  To better assess, 
  you would need to build the model and then perform sensitivity tests for different model scenarios.
